    en: "Residents of mobile home parks in New York have specific protections under Real Property Law 233. The park owner cannot evict without good cause, cannot unreasonably block the sale of a mobile home to a new buyer, and has to give at least 90 days' notice of a rent increase or a park closure. Many mobile home residents own the home but rent the lot — an unusual setup that the law addresses. Rent increases above 3% trigger additional protections under the 2019 HSTPA. A closing park owes relocation costs to residents who cannot find another suitable site."
